text: This will be NASA special report number 237, 14 minutes 30 seconds. Coming in 3, 2, 1. NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration presents a special report on the flight of Discovery, the next space shuttle mission. We have a go for main engine start. Seven, six, five. We have main engine start. We have a cutoff. We have an abort by the onboard computers of the Orbiter Discovery. Last June, an onboard computer on the space shuttle Discovery detected a valve failure and ordered a shutdown of the craft's main engines just a few seconds before liftoff. It was the first launch abort in the 12 mission history of the shuttle program and the second such abort in the 23 years of American manned space flight. The first occurred during the Gemini 6 mission in 1965. Jesse Moore is the acting shuttle director at NASA headquarters in Washington, D.C. Each engine, I should say, has a full redundancy in it in that the fuel lines, the controller of the engine, the fuel valves, the actuator valves are fully redundant and we started the launch attempt and we got into that count sequence a very short period of time and then we sensed we had a problem with one of the valves and engine number three. And the system immediately switch from channel A to the redundant channel B and started the operation. The general purpose computer at that time sensed that that we didn't have full redundancy on each of the engines, so it started a shutdown sequence. That's the way the system was designed, and at the time the shutdown sequence occurs, we inhibit the ignition command to the solar rocket boosters so the shuttle doesn't lift off. The faulty engine has been removed from Discovery and has gone through rigorous testing at NASA's National Space Technology Laboratories in Mississippi. We feel very confident that we will be able to identify the problem that we had on the launch pad and that we have since put a new engine back into Discovery. And the engines we have on Discovery now are the original engines that we had on board at the time we did a flight readiness firing back in the May time frame prior to our attempted launch in June. So we feel very confident that the engines will work fine on this upcoming launch of Discovery. NASA is planning to combine the cargo from what was to be the June flight, or 41D, and a second flight originally slated for August 29. The payloads and Discovery's flight now include the solar array, designed to study the possibilities of obtaining electrical power from the sun for future satellites, and the electrophoresis experiment, a 700-pound box designed by McDonnell Douglas Corporation to manufacture drug components in orbit for medical purposes. Both of these experiments were originally scheduled for Discovery's first flight. The astronauts will also deploy several communication satellites. We've added an SBS satellite, and we've also added a Telstar 3C satellite on board, a communication satellite. So the cargo for the 41D launch, now planned for August, includes most of the elements we originally had on Discovery, with the exception of a large-format camera, plus these two additional communication satellites. In the future, NASA would like to develop the flexibility of accommodating changing cargos and still remain on schedule with the shuttle manifest. Some payloads are more complicated to change out at the last minute than other payloads. And those payloads that are fairly complicated to change out typically involve a lot of software changes to the basic flight software. In other words, they require some integration with the overall flight software. and where you've got a high degree of integration, it takes longer to change them out. Where the software interface is very small, it's simple, you can make changes very quickly. And some cargos require very little software interfaces. And NASA has recently initiated another program which is going to allow us to achieve much more flexibility while flying more complicated scientific payloads, and that program is called the Hitchhiker Program. And it is being developed in two phases. One phase of it's in development out at the Goddard Space Flight Center, and this concept will use a kind of a flat plate that mounts on the side of the orbiter, and it only gets very simple power and command and telemetry interfaces, while it can still carry some fairly complicated scientific instruments. The other program is being developed at the Marshall Space Flight Center, and it has a little bit more capability in terms of carrying more experiments, but it essentially is designed along the same principle to maintain a very simple interface with the orbiter such that it only gets the essential power and data and command interfaces and it also can carry some fairly sophisticated and complex scientific instruments. These can be integrated at the very late stages of the game on board the shuttle so you don't have to go back and make major interface changes. The crew on Discovery's maiden flight will remain the same as was assigned to the 41D June mission. Hank Hartsfield, Commander. Michael Coates, pilot, mission specialists Judy Resnick, Steve Hawley, and Mike Mullane, and payload specialist Charlie Walker from McDonnell Douglas, who will be operating the electrophoresis experiment. Certain of these crew members had already trained for the release of these communication satellites, which, in effect, are the only two new additional payload elements we've put on board. Jesse Moore said that Atlantis, the last of the four space shuttle orbiters that make up the space shuttle fleet, is now in its final stages of development. Atlantis is doing super. We made a decision about four or five months ago to extend the delivery date of Atlantis until the April time frame of 1985. And we made this decision on the basis of carrying out some modifications that we wanted to implement in the program on Orbiter 102, which is Columbia, which is our first orbiter. We're bringing Columbia basically up to a fully operational status. It was our first vehicle and went through the development parts of the program, and we want to make it more operational and easier to turn around. Columbia's modifications will be completed about the end of this year. So in early to middle part of 1985, we'll have four operational vehicles. And our flight rate increases next year to about 11 flights. NASA has been discussing the possibility of building a fifth orbiter. We are implementing a structural spares program that buys some parts of a new orbiter. However, to implement a full orbiter takes a lot more than the structural spares program, and the agency is debating and evaluating the possibility of a fifth orbiter right now, so we know we have not made a decision yet. For many years, the possibility of flying into space was limited to trained astronauts. NASA is now looking into the possibility of flying ordinary citizens into space. Journalists, poets, writers, scientists, engineers or anyone with a particular experiment or job to do in space. We're very enthusiastic about it. The decision has not been made in terms of when the specific announcement will will come out regarding the citizen observer program, although I do expect that quite frankly to be very soon. What we're doing in the shuttle program, and that's something the administrator of the agency and others need to sit down and decide on the timing of that, and I cannot comment either on the criteria because I think we need to take a look at the criteria depending upon the type of program that we want to implement. But let me just say generally the criteria will be that there will be certain training requirements that we will ask the citizens to go through, obviously much less stringent than what the flight crews, the astronaut crews go through. to, medical standards would have to be met, etcetera. And once the program is officially announced we will then proceed writing the ground rules and doing the criteria for the evaluation and selection of the candidates in the program. As far as the shuttle activities are concerned, we are anticipating being able to fly private citizens from this program in the very late 1985 time frame, possibly early 86 time frame. And we have not settled on how many citizens we would fly per year, but it will be on the order of 2 to 3 flights per year we would like to invite private citizens to fly on. It's just a little premature to get more definitive than that at this point in time. We have been getting an inordinate amount of phone calls and letters from others around the world that really want to be on that list. So it's going to be a very challenging program for NASA to take all the applicants and screen all the applicants and select down to the very, very, very few because we see in our own astronaut recruiting program where we're trying to recruit permanent members of the astronaut corps that we get an enormous number of applications. And obviously the requirements for the astronaut program are fairly stringent. And even with those stringent requirements, we get an awful lot of applications. in this last selection process we went through. If my memory serves me correct, we got over 5,000 applications to be an astronaut. And we're only able to select about 16 to 17. So that's a very, very tough filter to go through. And we didn't even accept a lot of applicants that didn't meet some initial screening requirements. And we only received 5,000. So it's gonna be a tough process to screen down and narrow down to the few that will be selected for flight. But we're excited about the program and it will give citizens and various professional levels of life to take an opportunity to participate with us in this very exciting program and share some of the experiences at the this agency and its astronauts and others in the program have shared since the shuttle the inaugural flight back in April of 81. A number of companies are considering flying their experiments on the space shuttle. We have a program called a Join Endeavor program that we sign up mutually for the with a company in terms of trying to help get an initial experiment program going. And we provide assistance to them in terms of flying them free, on board the shuttle, in the early phases of their experimental program. And a classic example of what we've done so far is the McDonnell-Douglas Johnson & Johnson joint endeavor with NASA. And their efforts are thrust in the continuous-flow electrophoresis experiment, which we've flown several times before and are planning to fly on the upcoming discovery flight in August, and we're also flying their payload specialists. Charlie Walker will be on this crew. And Charlie is from the McDonnell Douglas Company and actually participated in the design of this continuous flow electrophoresis experiment. So, and we're providing him an opportunity to fly. Assisting him in flying and using his experimental equipment in space for doing this kind of research. And NASA believes that that is a very strong incentive and contribution to the industry of providing them early access to space, to demonstrate and test out some of their objectives so that later on, if they move in to a commercial endeavor in this thing, then NASA will get reimbursed for the flights after the program has proceeded past the very early phases. So, that's kind of an incentive, a very good incentive, I think, that the agency is very supportive of. Last February, two satellites deployed from the Space Shuttle Challenger were lost in space after small rocket motors on the satellites failed to place them in the desired geosynchronous orbit, 22,400 miles above Earth. On a later mission this year, NASA may attempt to rescue these satellites. You're referring to the events that occurred in February when we successfully deployed the Palapa B satellite and the Westar satellite. And then the nozzles on these rocket motors failed. And we have been working with the customers, in this case, Western Union for Westar and the Indonesian government for the Palapa spacecraft to see if they would request or want to request NASA to go and retrieve them. And we believe the situation is such today that we still are optimistic about being officially requested to go and retrieve those two satellites, although we still do not have a formal request from either the Indonesians or Western Union or the underwriters which represented those insurance companies which insured those two particular launches. However, NASA is doing everything to preserve the opportunity to retrieve those satellites and preparing for the opportunity to retrieve them in the event we are formally asked to go retrieve them, and that mission would take place in the early November time frame. And we believe, as I said, in an optimistic sense that NASA will be asked to go and retrieve those satellites, and we think we can successfully carry that out. NASA would command the satellites to fire their small engines, lowering their orbits so that Challenger could reach them. If that worked, the satellites would be ordered to slow their spin rate to about one revolution per minute. An astronaut wearing the jet-powered manned maneuvering unit could move from Challenger to rendezvous with the satellites. Yes, it will be very similar to the Solar Maximum mission where we will use our man maneuvering unit and an astronaut to go out and affix an attachment device to the satellite so that we can go and rendezvous with it with the shuttle and grapple it and bring it back into Cargo Bay and store it for its return back to Earth. We're very excited about the opportunity that we hope to have in terms of going to retrieve these satellites. I think the future potential of the shuttle is virtually unlimited and we're very excited about the potential of the shuttle. NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, has presented an interview with Jesse Moore, acting director of the Space Shuttle Program at NASA headquarters.
